###  Updating the parent component in a Transition

You can update a parent component’s state from the ` useTransition ` call,
too. For example, this ` TabButton ` component wraps its ` onClick ` logic in
a Transition:



    export default function TabButton({ children, isActive, onClick }) {  


      const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();  


      if (isActive) {  


        return <b>{children}</b>  


      }  


      return (  


        <button onClick={() => {  


          startTransition(() => {  


            onClick();  


          });  


        }}>  


          {children}  


        </button>  


      );  


    }

Because the parent component updates its state inside the ` onClick ` event
handler, that state update gets marked as a Transition. This is why, like in
the earlier example, you can click on “Posts” and then immediately click
“Contact”. Updating the selected tab is marked as a Transition, so it does not
block user interactions.

